Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Root-cause navigation was imprecise-to-useless: the edge↔pipeline
mapping guessed by execution-time windows, every recipe's ~hundred
injected `export …` prefix lines were recorded as pipelines (the
'100000 events'), a failed build's error text was captured but never
rendered, and nothing showed 'this started that'.

- Exact causality: katirun's edge reporter tags the worker thread with
  the edge whose recipe is running (re-seeded across the brush recipe
  thread like the pipeline uid); every pipeline record stamps
  `edge_out`. review.map_ids joins on it — NO time-window fallback,
  the tag is the only linkage.

- The make export prefix no longer generates provenance: the recipe
  runner receives it SEPARATELY (RecipeRunner/run_command gained a
  prefix parameter), applies it to the same shell via run_string
  (vars/exports land, nothing recorded), and only the user's recipe
  goes through the recording path. $(shell …) gets the same
  treatment. A synthetic failing build drops from 132 recorded
  pipelines per recipe to the recipe's own 2.

- Failures are surfaced: kati's executor keeps the TAIL ~1KB of each
  recipe's merged output and ships it on the edge's Done report;
  mark_build_edge_done stores it in output_excerpt. The edge detail
  pane renders it (red on failure); the box overview leads with a
  ── FAILURES ── section (failed edges with their excerpt's last line
  + failed pipelines) fed by review.box_summary's new failures list.

- 'This started that': the Pipelines detail pane shows the causal
  neighborhood via review.pipeline_context — the parent pipeline (↑),
  the pipelines it started (↳, failed ones marked), and the build edge
  whose recipe it is (⚒).

